Capstone Project - Detection of User Churn @ Sparkify.org¶

This workspace contains a tiny subset (128MB) of the full dataset available (12GB). Feel free to use this workspace to build your project, or to explore a smaller subset with Spark before deploying your cluster on the cloud. Instructions for setting up your Spark cluster is included in the last lesson of the Extracurricular Spark Course content.

You can follow the steps below to guide your data analysis and model building portion of this project.

Load and Clean Dataset¶

In this workspace, the mini-dataset file is mini_sparkify_event_data.json. Load and clean the dataset, checking for invalid or missing data - for example, records without userids or sessionids.

# Now we clean the dataframe further. starting with removing all the records without a non-null userId

Following the cleaning process, the quantity of nulls markedly decreased across all rows without a valid userId. The cleaning process for 15 of the 18 variables in the Spark DataFrame is now complete. Nonetheless, the variables artists, length, and song continue to exhibit a significant amount (i.e., 50046) of nulls. It is pissible to eliminate all rows containing nulls in the Spark DataFrame; however, this may result in the loss of significant information which could is problematic.

Let's examine the records that display nulls in the variables artists, length, & song.

In [168]:
# Taking a temporary snap of df_clean ad checking the nulls in artist col

All of the nulls in the variables artists, lengthand song appear in the same records. Therefore, these records might correspond to user-interactions without the user playing a song.¶

In [171]:

The records containing nulls in the variables artists, length, and song are associated with a significant number of separate users engaging with our service at various periods. Consequently, we ought to retain those data as they constitute legitimate observations of user interactions, despite the absence of music playback by the user.

So next, we aim to convert the timestamp variable ts and the registration variable in the Spark DataFrame, into two new variables: timeStamp and registration_timeStamp, respectively. Both should display the time and date in a human readable format.

Introducing new variable - timeStamp (valid string representing date-time )¶

In [172]:
# convert datetime objects to its equivalent string
get_timeStamp = udf(lambda x: datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(x / 1000.0).strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"))

# Apply to the ts variable
df_clean = df_clean.withColumn("timeStamp", get_timeStamp(df_clean.ts))

Introducing new variable - memberSince¶

In [176]:
get_membership = udf(lambda x,y: float((x-y)/(1000*60*60*24)))

df_clean = df_clean.withColumn("memberSince", get_membership(df_clean.ts, df.registration))
df_clean = df_clean.withColumn("memberSince", df_clean["memberSince"].cast(IntegerType()))

Let's find out the start date and the end date of the data records?

  • Answer - The dataset has about two months of data from 01st October to 3rd December in the year of 2018.
In [194]:
spark.sql('''
          SELECT min(timeStamp) AS start, max(timeStamp) AS end
          FROM user_log_table 
          '''

The Cancellation Confirmation page is where a user is directed after they have confirmed their decision to cancel their service which makes it essential to identify the churn.

In [200]:
# Let's check how many users have cancelled the service or not 

spark.sql('''
        SELECT auth, COUNT(userId) AS No_of_Users
        FROM user_log_table
        GROUP BY auth
        ORDER BY No_of_Users DESC
        '''
         ).show()

+---------+-----------+
|     auth|No_of_Users|
+---------+-----------+
|Logged In|     278102|
|Cancelled|         52|
+---------+-----------+
In [201]:
df_clean.select(["userId", "page"]).where(df_clean.page == "Cancellation Confirmation").count() # Num of users got churned
Out[201]:
52

So, out of total 278,154 records in this dataset, and the variable auth flags 52 thus cancelled.

          WHERE page == 'Cancellation Confirmation'

         ).toPandas()

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

When you're working with the full dataset, perform EDA by loading a small subset of the data and doing basic manipulations within Spark. In this workspace, you are already provided a small subset of data you can explore.

Define Churn¶

Once you've done some preliminary analysis, create a column Churn to use as the label for your model. I suggest using the Cancellation Confirmation events to define your churn, which happen for both paid and free users. As a bonus task, you can also look into the Downgrade events.

In [210]:
df_clean_backup = df_clean
df_clean_backup
Out[210]:
DataFrame[artist: string, auth: string, firstName: string, gender: string, itemInSession: bigint, lastName: string, length: double, level: string, location: string, method: string, page: string, registration: bigint, sessionId: bigint, song: string, status: bigint, ts: bigint, userAgent: string, userId: string, timeStamp: string, registration_timeStamp: string, memberSince: int]
In [224]:
df_clean = df_clean_backup
In [231]:
# Creating a flag where if users get churned then 1 else 0
churnEvent = udf(lambda page: 1 if page == "Cancellation Confirmation" else 0, IntegerType())
In [232]:
# Adding coloumn `isChurn` to df_clean
df_clean = df_clean.withColumn("isChurn", churnEvent("page"))

Now we'll define a new variable Churn that contains all of the records of users who later cancel the service. We may use a SQL windows function to find the maximum value of the isChurn variable for each userId

In [248]:
# SQL query with a Windows function enabled
spark.sql('''
          SELECT userId, max(isChurn)
          OVER (PARTITION BY userId)
          FROM user_log_table 
          ORDER BY  timeStamp 
          '''
         ).show()

In [249]:
usrWindow = Window \
    .partitionBy('userId') \
    .orderBy(desc('ts')) \
    .rangeBetween(Window.unboundedPreceding, Window.unboundedFollowing)
In [250]:
df_clean_backuo02 = df_clean
In [252]:
df_clean = df_clean.withColumn('Churn', max('isChurn').over(usrWindow))
In [253]:

Approx 16% of the records in the given dataset belong to churned users

Explore Data¶

Once you've defined churn, perform some exploratory data analysis to observe the behavior for users who stayed vs users who churned. You can start by exploring aggregates on these two groups of users, observing how much of a specific action they experienced per a certain time unit or number of songs played.

In [254]:
df_clean.createOrReplaceTempView("user_log_table")

Introducing a new variable downFreq¶

This new var downFreq shows the frequency of a user downgrading the current service already. It has only one value for every user's records.

In [269]:

Those who keep up the service usually interact with us more often. Continually customers have more sessions over time (sessionId) and listen to more tracks during sessions (itemInSession). On the length of the songs they perform (length) or in the status codes of their HTTP requests—e.g., Bad Request 400 Error—there is no significant variation between the two groups.

Introducing a new variable usrInteractions¶

This new var usrInteractions shows the total number of interactions of a user.

In [286]:
df_clean  = df_clean.withColumn("usrInteractions", count ("itemInSession").over(usrWindow))
In [287]:
df_clean.select(["itemInSession", "timeStamp", "page", ("sessionId") , "usrInteractions"])\
           .where(df_clean.userId == "77")\
           .sort("ts").collect()

Gender [Female/Male]¶

  • The categorical variable gender takes any of two possible values, F or M.
In [289]:
spark.sql('''
          SELECT Churn, gender, COUNT(DISTINCT userId) AS num_of_users
          FROM user_log_table 
          GROUP BY Churn, gender
          ORDER BY Churn DESC, gender
         
          '''
         ).show()

+-----+------+------------+
|Churn|gender|num_of_users|
+-----+------+------------+
|    1|     F|          20|
|    1|     M|          32|
|    0|     F|          84|
|    0|     M|          89|
+-----+------+------------+

We will employ a statistical proportions test to assess whether females and males have an equal likelihood of cancelling the service (null hypothesis).

Definition of p-value

In null hypothesis significance testing, the p-value represents the likelihood of acquiring test results that are at least as extreme as those observed as dramatic as the outcomes obtained, assuming the null hypothesis is valid.

A diminutive p-value indicates that an exceptional observed outcome would be highly improbable under the null hypothesis.

In [293]:
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

count = np.array([20, 32])
nobs  = np.array([(20+84), (32+89)])


stat, pval  = proportions_ztest(count, nobs, value=None, alternative='two-sided', prop_var=False)

print('{0:0.2f} test statistic for the z-test'.format(stat))
print('{0:0.2f} p-value for the z-test'.format(pval))

-1.28 test statistic for the z-test
0.20 p-value for the z-test

We cannot dismiss the null hypothesis that gender does not influence churn likelihood, as the p-value of 0.201 is excessively high. There is a 20 percent probability of acquiring the observed statistic or a more extreme value supporting the alternative hypothesis.

Location [city & state]¶

The categorical variable location indicates the cities and states of users' residence in USA. Our primary focus is on state-specific locations, and we compile the user count accordingly.

In [294]:
df_clean = df_clean.withColumn('city', split(df['location'], ",").getItem(0))\
        .withColumn('state', split(df_clean['location'], ",").getItem(1))
In [296]:
df_clean.createOrReplaceTempView("user_log_table")
In [297]:
df_clean
Out[297]:
DataFrame[artist: string, auth: string, firstName: string, gender: string, itemInSession: bigint, lastName: string, length: double, level: string, location: string, method: string, page: string, registration: bigint, sessionId: bigint, song: string, status: bigint, ts: bigint, userAgent: string, userId: string, timeStamp: string, registration_timeStamp: string, memberSince: int, isChurn: int, Churn: int, downgrade_event: int, downFreq: bigint, usrInteractions: bigint, city: string, state: string]
In [298]:
loc_churned  = spark.sql('''
        SELECT state, COUNT(DISTINCT userId) AS user_churned
        FROM user_log_table
        WHERE Churn = 1
        GROUP BY state
        ORDER BY user_churned DESC
        '''
        ).toPandas()
In [300]:
loc_churned   = loc_churned.set_index('state')
In [299]:
loc_active  = spark.sql('''
        SELECT state, COUNT(DISTINCT userId) AS active_users
        FROM user_log_table
        WHERE Churn = 0
        GROUP BY state
        ORDER BY active_users DESC
        '''
        ).toPandas()
In [302]:
loc_active = loc_active.set_index('state')
In [303]:
loc_by_state = pd.concat([loc_churned.groupby('state').sum(), loc_active.groupby('state').sum()], \
                              axis=1, join="outer", sort=True)
In [306]:
loc_by_state = loc_by_state.sort_values(by=['active_users', 'user_churned'], ascending=False)
In [316]:
plt.title('Location based users @ Sparkify.org', fontsize=25)

ax = loc_by_state['active_users'].plot(kind='bar', \
                                               color ='c', figsize=(15, 6), legend=True, fontsize=10)

ax = loc_by_state['user_churned'].plot(kind='bar', \
                                              color ='b', legend=True, fontsize=15)
ax.set_xlabel("State", fontsize=15)
ax.set_ylabel("# of Users", fontsize=15)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

The majority of Sparify.org users reside in states with substantial populations. In the limited dataset, Sparify's churn rate in California, Texas, and Florida is lower than the overall churn rate of 52 out of 225, or 23 percent. Nevertheless, Spotify's turnover rate in some less populous states remains elevated.

Artist¶

The variable artist display the name of the artist singing the song played by the user.

In [317]:
# How many artists are there in the data set?
spark.sql('''
        SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT Artist) AS no_of_artists
        FROM user_log_table 
        '''
        ).show()

|no_of_artists|
+-------------+

In [318]:
# How many songs were played from the most played artist?
artist_active = spark.sql('''
        SELECT Artist, COUNT(Artist) AS active_users 
        FROM user_log_table 
        WHERE Churn == 0
        GROUP BY Artist 
        ORDER BY active_users DESC 
        
        '''
        ).toPandas()
In [319]:
artist_active = artist_active.set_index('Artist')
In [321]:
artist_churn = spark.sql('''
        SELECT Artist, COUNT(Artist) AS user_churned 
        FROM user_log_table 
        WHERE Churn == 1
        GROUP BY Artist 
        ORDER BY user_churned DESC 
        
        '''
        ).toPandas()
In [322]:
artist_churn = artist_churn.set_index('Artist')
In [328]:
df_artist= pd.concat([artist_active.groupby('Artist').sum(), artist_churn.groupby('Artist').sum()], \
                              axis=1, join="outer", sort=True)
In [329]:
df_artist = df_artist.sort_values(by=['active_users', 'user_churned'], ascending=False)

Page¶

In [11]:
pages  = spark.sql('''
        SELECT page, Churn, COUNT(page) AS no_of_records
        FROM user_log_table
        GROUP BY Churn, page
        ORDER BY page DESC
        '''
        ).toPandas()
In [22]:
pages_nochurn = pages[pages.Churn == 0]
pages_nochurn = pages_nochurn.rename(columns={"no_of_records": "active_users"})
pages_nochurn = pages_nochurn.drop(['Churn'], axis=1)
pages_nochurn = pages_nochurn.set_index('page')   

pages_churn = pages[pages.Churn == 1]
pages_churn = pages_churn.rename(columns={"no_of_records": "users_churned"})
pages_churn = pages_churn.drop(['Churn'], axis=1)
pages_churn = pages_churn.set_index('page') 

df_page = pd.concat([pages_nochurn, pages_churn], axis=1, join="inner")
In [23]:
df_page = df_page.sort_values(by=['active_users', 'users_churned'], ascending=True)

What is the average number of tracks played by churned users prior to subscription cancellation?

In [35]:
is_confCancel = spark.sql('''
            SELECT userID, page, ts, CASE WHEN page = 'Cancellation Confirmation' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END AS is_home 
            FROM user_log_table 
            WHERE ((page = 'NextSong') OR (page = 'Cancellation Confirmation')) AND Churn == 1
            '''
            )

is_confCancel.createOrReplaceTempView("is_confCancel_table")
In [38]:
is_confCancel
Out[38]:
DataFrame[userID: string, page: string, ts: bigint, is_home: int]
In [39]:
cumulative_sum = spark.sql('''
            SELECT * , SUM(is_home) 
            OVER (PARTITION BY userID ORDER BY ts DESC ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) AS period 
            FROM is_confCancel_table
            '''
            )
            
cumulative_sum.createOrReplaceTempView("period_table")
In [40]:
spark.sql('''
          SELECT INT(ROUND (AVG(count_results),0)) AS average_no_of_songs
          FROM (SELECT COUNT(*) AS count_results FROM period_table \
          GROUP BY userID, period, page HAVING page = 'NextSong') AS counts
          '''
          ).show()

          FROM user_log_table

          ORDER BY Churn DESC

         ).show()

In [56]:
df_statistics = spark.sql('''
      WITH page_counts AS( 
      SELECT userId, 
      MAX(Churn)                                                      AS Churn, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Thumbs Up'        THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS thumbs_up,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Home'             THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS home,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Add to Playlist'  THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS playlist_count, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Add Friend'       THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS friends,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Roll Advert'      THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS advert,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Logout'           THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS logout,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Thumbs Down'      THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS thumbs_down,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Downgrade'        THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS downgrade,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Settings'         THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS settings,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Help'             THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS help,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'About'            THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS about,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Upgrade'          THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS upgrade,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Save Settings'    THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS save_settings, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Error'            THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS error, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Submit Upgrade'   THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS submit_upgrade, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Submit Downgrade' THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS submit_downgrade,
      COUNT(DISTINCT sessionId)                                       AS session_count, 
      MAX (memberSince)                                        AS membership_days, 
      SUM(length/(60*60))                                             AS usage_hours 
      
      FROM user_log_table 
      GROUP BY userId) 
      SELECT Churn, 
      ROUND(AVG(thumbs_up),1)           AS thumbs_up,
      ROUND(AVG(home),1)                AS home,
      ROUND(AVG(playlist_count),1)      AS playlist_count, 
      ROUND(AVG(friends),1)             AS friends, 
      ROUND(AVG(advert),1)              AS advert, 
      ROUND(AVG(logout),1)              AS logout,
      ROUND(AVG(thumbs_down),1)         AS thumbs_down, 
      ROUND(AVG(downgrade),1)           AS downgrade, 
      ROUND(AVG(settings),1)            AS settings, 
      ROUND(AVG(help),1)                AS help, 
      ROUND(AVG(about),1)               AS about, 
      ROUND(AVG(upgrade),1)             AS upgrade,
      ROUND(AVG(save_settings),1)       AS save_settings,
      ROUND(AVG(error),1)               AS error, 
      ROUND(AVG(submit_upgrade),1)      AS submit_upgrade,
      ROUND(AVG(submit_downgrade),1)    AS submit_downgrade, 
      ROUND(AVG(session_count),1)       AS session_count,
      ROUND(AVG(membership_days),1)     AS membership_days,
      ROUND(AVG(usage_hours),1)         AS usage_hours
      
      FROM page_counts 
      GROUP BY Churn
      '''
      ).toPandas()

In [79]:
getHourOfDay  = udf(lambda x: datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(x / 1000.0).hour)
getDayOfMonth = udf(lambda x: datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(x / 1000.0).day)
getWeekday    = udf(lambda x: datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(x / 1000.0).strftime('%w'))
getDate       = udf(lambda x: datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(x / 1000.0).strftime('%m/%d/%Y'))

df_weekday_churn   = df_weekday_churn.set_index('weekDay')
In [155]:
df_weekday = pd.concat([df_weekday_active, df_weekday_churn], axis=1, join="outer")
In [156]:
# Weekdays are represented as decimal numbers where Sunday: 0 and Saturday: 6.
dict = {'0':'Sunday','1':'Monday','2':'Tuesday','3':'Wednesday','4':'Thursday','5':'Friday','6':'Saturday'}
df_weekday.index = df_weekday.index.map(dict)

          GROUP BY dateStamp

          '''
          ).toPandas()

userAgent¶

The User-Agent request header is a unique string that allows servers and network peers to determine the program, operating system, vendor, and/or version of the requesting user agent.

  • Mobile Device
  • PC Desktop

  • Tablet

  • https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/User-Agent

In [172]:
userAgent_count = spark.sql('''
        SELECT userAgent,COUNT(userId) AS num_of_records
        FROM user_log_table
        GROUP BY userAgent
        ORDER BY num_of_records DESC
''').toPandas()

In [283]:
is_mobile = udf(lambda x: 1 if 'Phone' in x else 0, IntegerType())
df_clean = df_clean.withColumn("mobile_android_ios", is_mobile(df_clean.userAgent))

is_tablet = udf(lambda x: 1 if 'iPad' in x else 0, IntegerType())
df_clean = df_clean.withColumn("tablet", is_tablet(df_clean.userAgent))

is_win = udf(lambda x: 1 if 'Windows' in x and not 'Phone' in x and not 'Linux' in x else 0, IntegerType())
df_clean = df_clean.withColumn("windows_pc", is_win(df_clean.userAgent))    

is_linux = udf(lambda x: 1 if 'Ubuntu' in x or 'Linux' in x or 'Debian' in x and not 'Phone' in x else 0, IntegerType())
df_clean = df_clean.withColumn("linux_debian", is_linux(df_clean.userAgent))

is_mac = udf(lambda x: 1 if 'Mac' in x and not 'Phone' in x else 0, IntegerType())
df_clean = df_clean.withColumn("apple_mac", is_mac(df_clean.userAgent))

Feature Engineering¶

Once you've familiarized yourself with the data, build out the features you find promising to train your model on. To work with the full dataset, you can follow the following steps.

  • Write a script to extract the necessary features from the smaller subset of data
  • Ensure that your script is scalable, using the best practices discussed in Lesson 3
  • Try your script on the full data set, debugging your script if necessary

If you are working in the classroom workspace, you can just extract features based on the small subset of data contained here. Be sure to transfer over this work to the larger dataset when you work on your Spark cluster.

In [350]:
featuresThatMatters = spark.sql(
      '''
      SELECT userId, 
      MAX(Churn)                                                      AS label, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Error'            THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS error_count, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Add Friend'       THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS friends_count, 
      COUNT(CASE when page = 'Roll Advert'      THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS advert_count,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Add to Playlist'  THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS playlist_count, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Thumbs Up'        THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS thumbs_up, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Thumbs Down'      THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS thumbs_down, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Downgrade'        THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS downgrade,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Upgrade'          THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS upgrade,
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Submit Upgrade'   THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS submit_upgrade, 
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'Submit Downgrade' THEN 1 ELSE null END) AS submit_downgrade,
      
      INT  (Case WHEN FIRST (level) ='free' THEN True ELSE False END) AS FIRST_level_free,
      INT  (Case WHEN FIRST (level) ='paid' THEN True ELSE False END) AS FIRST_level_paid,
      INT  (Case WHEN LAST (level)  ='free' THEN True ELSE False END) AS LAST_level_free,
      INT  (Case WHEN LAST (level)  ='paid' THEN True ELSE False END) AS LAST_level_paid,
    
      
      SUM(downgrade_event)                                            AS phase,
      MAX(mobile_android_ios)                                         AS mobile,
      MAX(apple_mac)                                                  AS Apple_Mac,
      MAX(linux_debian)                                               AS Linux,
      MAX(windows_pc)                                                 AS Windows,
      AVG(hour)                                                       AS hour,
      AVG(day)                                                        AS day,
      AVG(weekDay)                                                    AS weekday,
      
      INT(MAX(CASE WHEN gender = 'F' THEN True ELSE False END))         AS female,
      INT(MAX(CASE WHEN state  = ' CA'       THEN True ELSE False END)) AS CA,
      INT(MAX(CASE WHEN state  = ' TX'       THEN True ELSE False END)) AS TX,
      INT(MAX(CASE WHEN state  = ' FL'       THEN True ELSE False END)) AS FL,
      INT(MAX(CASE WHEN state  = ' NY-NJ-PA' THEN True ELSE False END)) AS NY_NJ_PA,
      
      MAX (memberSince)                                          AS membership_days, 
      COUNT(DISTINCT sessionId)                                         AS session_count,
      MAX(usrInteractions)                                              AS items_count,   
      COUNT(CASE WHEN page = 'NextSong'         THEN 1 ELSE null END)   AS song_count, 
      SUM(length/(60*60))                                               AS usage_hours
      
      FROM user_log_table 
      GROUP BY userId
      '''
      )
In [351]:
featuresThatMatters.createOrReplaceTempView('featuresThatMatters');
In [352]:
featuresThatMatters = featuresThatMatters.na.drop()
In [353]:
df_features = featuresThatMatters.toPandas()
df_features

Modeling¶

Split the full dataset into train, test, and validation sets. Test out several of the machine learning methods you learned. Evaluate the accuracy of the various models, tuning parameters as necessary. Determine your winning model based on test accuracy and report results on the validation set. Since the churned users are a fairly small subset, I suggest using F1 score as the metric to optimize.

In [319]:
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline
from pyspark.ml.regression import LinearRegression
from pyspark.ml.tuning import CrossValidator, ParamGridBuilder
from pyspark.ml.evaluation import MulticlassClassificationEvaluator
from pyspark.ml.feature import CountVectorizer, IDF, PCA, RegexTokenizer, VectorAssembler, Normalizer, StandardScaler
from pyspark.ml.classification import LogisticRegression, RandomForestClassifier, GBTClassifier, LinearSVC, NaiveBayes

Assembling Feature Vector¶

  • Creating a vector from the combined columns of all of the features

  • Here, we use VectorAssembler is a transformer that converts a list of columns into one vector column. It is useful for integrating raw features and features generated by various feature transformers into a single feature vector for training machine learning models such as logistic regression and decision trees.

  • VectorAssembler accepts the following column types:

    • numeric
    • boolean
    • vector

  • Source: https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/api/python/reference/api/pyspark.ml.feature.VectorAssembler.html

In [375]:
assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=["userId",
                                       "error_count",
                                       "friends_count",
                                       "advert_count",
                                       "playlist_count", 
                                       "thumbs_up",
                                       "thumbs_down",
                                       "downgrade", 
                                       "upgrade",
                                       "submit_upgrade",
                                       "submit_downgrade", 
                                       "FIRST_level_paid",
                                       "LAST_level_paid",
                                       "phase", 
                                       "mobile", 
                                       "Apple_Mac", 
                                       "Linux", 
                                       "Windows", 
                                       "hour", 
                                       "day", 
                                       "weekday", 
                                       "female", 
                                       "CA", 
                                       "TX", 
                                       "FL", 
                                       "NY_NJ_PA", 
                                       "membership_days",
                                       "session_count",
                                       "items_count",
                                       "song_count",
                                       "usage_hours"],
                            outputCol="inFeatures")

Vector Normalization¶

Normalize a vector to have unit norm using the given p-norm.

  • Source: https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/api/python/reference/api/pyspark.ml.feature.Normalizer.html
In [381]:
scaler = Normalizer(inputCol="inFeatures", outputCol="features")

Random Forest Classifier¶

In [382]:
# Random Forest classifier
rfc           = RandomForestClassifier() 
pipeline_rfc  = Pipeline(stages=[assembler, scaler, rfc])
In [383]:
paramgrid_rfc = ParamGridBuilder()\
.build()

evaluator=MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(metricName="f1")

crossval= CrossValidator(estimator=pipeline_rfc,  
                         estimatorParamMaps=paramgrid_rfc,
                         evaluator=evaluator, 
                         numFolds=5)
In [384]:
start = time.time()

cvModel_rfc = crossval.fit(train)

end = time.time()
print(f'Total time : {end-start} seconds')

Total time : 693.8746218681335 seconds
In [385]:
results_rfc = cvModel_rfc.transform(test)
results_rfc

Logistic Regression¶

In [418]:
lr =  LogisticRegression(maxIter=10, regParam=0.0, elasticNetParam=0)
pipeline_lr = Pipeline(stages=[assembler, scaler, lr ])
In [419]:
paramgrid =ParamGridBuilder()\
.addGrid(lr.regParam, [0.0, 0,1])\
.addGrid(lr.maxIter, [10])\
.build()


evaluator=MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(metricName="f1")

crossval= CrossValidator(estimator=pipeline_lr,  
                         estimatorParamMaps=paramgrid,
                         evaluator = evaluator , 
                         numFolds=5)
